gentId\":\"a713062a872c2d8d3\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01NTuMV5ZbpfAYdR7H5mQQ8y\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01H6xkMdUbRJbb54L58NNMnv\",\"uuid\":\"6363e381-48dc-4839-8779-75ff09717891\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T09:56:44.364Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"6045d8ec-bf58-4e40-89fe-f1126e592103\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\"slug\":\"synthetic-puzzling-torvalds\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"6363e381-48dc-4839-8779-75ff09717891\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T09:58:29.750Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01WvAaUaCwYKPHjmQmDQV1R1\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01XABzs22tocBvpkxp9ccXnd\",\"name\":\"Write\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/docs/requirements/device-auth-login/review-02.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 02\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-03-14\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\nReview 01 raised 14 items. Assessing each against the current code on `feat/device-auth-login`:\\n\\n- [ ] **Item 1 (Critical): Missing HTTP client timeout** -- STILL OUTSTANDING. `NewClient(nil)` still creates `&http.Client{}` with zero timeout (client.go:47). No change since review-01.\\n- [ ] **Item 2 (Critical): Missing `t.Parallel()` comments on `t.Setenv` tests** -- STILL OUTSTANDING. `base_url_test.go` and `store_test.go:TestLookupToken` still use `t.Setenv` without `t.Parallel()` and without a comment explaining why.\\n- [ ] **Item 3 (Important): Confusing `waitForApproval` control flow** -- STILL OUTSTANDING. The `case \\\"\\\"` + later `if result.Error == \\\"\\\"` double-check pattern remains (login.go:108-129).\\n- [ ] **Item 4 (Important): Initial poll interval not capped to `maxPollInterval`** -- STILL OUTSTANDING. Only the `slow_down` case caps to `maxPollInterval` (login.go:93-96).\\n- [ ] **Item 5 (Important): Windows `openBrowser` command injection via `cmd /c start`** -- STILL OUTSTANDING. Raw `browserURL` is passed to `cmd /c start` instead of the re-serialized `u.String()` (login.go:157).\\n- [ ] **Item 6 (Important): TOCTOU race in `SaveToken`** -- STILL OUTSTANDING. No file lock or comment added (store.go:46-61).\\n- [ ] **Item 7 (Important): Hardcoded `~/.config/entire/` ignoring `XDG_CONFIG_HOME`** -- STILL OUTSTANDING. Though this is consistent with `versioncheck`, so acceptable to defer.\\n- [ ] **Item 8 (Important): `browserOpener` package-level var has no comment** -- STILL OUTSTANDING. No comment explaining the testing seam (login.go:22).\\n- [ ] **Item 9 (Suggestion): Strict decode for `StartDeviceAuth` may break on server additions** -- STILL OUTSTANDING. `decodeJSONStrict` used for start response (client.go:90). Defensible choice.\\n- [ ] **Item 10 (Suggestion): `time.After` in poll loop creates leaked timers** -- STILL OUTSTANDING (login.go:134).\\n- [ ] **Item 11 (Suggestion): Double-buffering in `decodeJSONWithOptions`** -- STILL OUTSTANDING (client.go:174-188).\\n- [ ] **Item 12 (Suggestion): No \\\"already logged in\\\" check** -- STILL OUTSTANDING.\\n- [ ] **Item 13 (Suggestion): Smoke script depends on python3** -- STILL OUTSTANDING (scripts/local-device-auth-smoke.sh:37-57).\\n- [ ] **Item 14 (Suggestion): Client-side expiry races with server** -- Acknowledged as inherent. No action needed.\\n\\n**Summary: No items from review-01 have been addressed.** All critical and important issues remain.\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n1. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go:123-128] `PollDeviceAuth` swallows non-JSON error responses during polling, causing infinite retry**\\n\\n   When the server returns a non-200 status with a body that is not valid JSON (e.g., a `502 Bad Gateway` with an HTML body from a reverse proxy, or a `500 Internal Server Error` with plain text), `readAPIErrorResponse` falls through to its `fmt.Errorf(\\\"status %d: %s\\\", ...)` path, returning a non-nil `error`. In `PollDeviceAuth`, this `err != nil` path returns `nil, fmt.Errorf(...)`, which propagates up to `waitForApproval` line 104 and immediately terminates the poll loop with an error.\\n\\n   However, when the server returns a non-200 status with valid JSON that has an empty `error` field (e.g., `{\\\"message\\\": \\\"rate limited\\\"}`), `readAPIErrorResponse` sees `strings.TrimSpace(apiErr.Error) != \\\"\\\"` is false, falls through to the plain-text path, and returns an error. This is fine.\\n\\n   But there is a real issue: when the server returns a non-200 response with `{\\\"error\\\": \\\"some_unknown_error_code\\\"}`, `readAPIErrorResponse` succeeds, and `PollDeviceAuth` returns `&DeviceAuthPoll{Error: \\\"some_unknown_error_code\\\"}`. This hits the `default` case in the switch (login.go:120-121) and correctly terminates. So this path is actually OK.\\n\\n   **The actual critical issue** is: if the server transiently returns HTTP 500 with `{\\\"error\\\": \\\"internal_server_error\\\"}` or similar, the poll loop will terminate immediately rather than retrying. Per RFC 8628 Section 3.5, only `authorization_pending` and `slow_down` are non-terminal -- all other error codes (including unknown ones) should be treated as terminal. However, transient server errors (5xx) are _not_ part of the RFC error code space and should ideally be retried with backoff rather than treated as a terminal device auth failure.\\n\\n   Suggested fix: In `PollDeviceAuth`, when the HTTP status is 5xx, return a retriable error or return the result with `Error: \\\"authorization_pending\\\"` equivalent to allow the loop to continue. Alternatively, add retry logic in `waitForApproval` for poll errors:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   result, err := client.PollDeviceAuth(ctx, deviceCode)\\n   if err != nil {\\n       // Transient network/server errors should not immediately terminate\\n       // the poll loop. Log and continue to next poll interval.\\n       continue\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n   This is important because the device auth flow can run for 5-15 minutes, and a single transient 500 during that window should not abort the entire login process.\\n\\n2. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:87-96] No unit tests for `waitForApproval` or `runLogin`**\\n\\n   There are no unit tests in a `login_test.go` file. All test coverage comes from integration tests that spawn a subprocess. This means:\\n   - The `slow_down` backoff logic is completely untested (no integration test exercises it).\\n   - The `maxPollInterval` cap is untested.\\n   - The client-side `maxExpiresIn` cap is untested.\\n   - The \\\"device authorization completed without a token\\\" edge case (empty `AccessToken` on success) is untested.\\n   - The `default` error case (unknown error code) is untested.\\n\\n   These are all branches in `waitForApproval` that have zero coverage. Unit tests with a mock `auth.Client` (or an interface) would be straightforward. Alternatively, add integration tests for at least the `slow_down` and unknown-error-code paths.\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n3. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go:45-53] `NewClient` captures `apiurl.BaseURL()` at construction time, which reads env var once**\\n\\n   This is actually good design (prevents mid-flow URL changes), but it creates a subtle testing issue. In `login.go:41`, `auth.NewClient(nil)` is called, which reads `ENTIRE_API_BASE_URL` from the environment. The integration tests set this env var on the subprocess, so they work correctly. But if someone writes a unit test for `runLogin` in the future and uses `t.Setenv`, the `NewClient(nil)` inside `runLogin` would read the test's env var. This is fine -- just noting that `Client` is not injectable into `runLogin`, making it harder to unit test without a real HTTP server.\\n\\n   Suggested improvement for testability: Accept a `*auth.Client` parameter in `runLogin`, or use a `ClientFactory` function that can be overridden in tests. This would enable unit testing of the login flow without a subprocess.\\n\\n4. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/store.go:90-131] `save()` uses `os.CreateTemp` then `Chmod`, but file may briefly have default umask permissions**\\n\\n   The temp file is created by `os.CreateTemp` with the default permissions (typically `0o666` masked by umask, often `0o644`). Then `Chmod(0o600)` is called. Between creation and chmod, the file exists with wider permissions. This window is tiny and the file is in a `0o700` directory, so the risk is minimal. However, `os.OpenFile` with explicit permissions would avoid the race entirely:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   tmpPath := filepath.Join(dir, \\\".auth_tmp_\\\"+randomSuffix())\\n   tmpFile, err := os.OpenFile(tmpPath, os.O_CREATE|os.O_WRONLY|os.O_EXCL, 0o600)\\n   ```\\n\\n   This is a defense-in-depth suggestion for a security-sensitive file (it contains auth tokens).\\n\\n5. **[cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/login_test.go:70-84] Happy-path test approves via the mock server's `/approve` endpoint, but does not verify the request body**\\n\\n   The `/approve` endpoint handler (line 57-61) unconditionally sets `approved = true` without checking any request parameters. In a real flow, the approval would be authenticated. This is fine for a mock, but the test should at least verify that the approval URL received by the CLI contains the expected query parameters (the `code=ABCD-EFGH` part). The test extracts `approvalURL` on line 70 but only sends a POST to it without asserting its structure.\\n\\n   Minor, but would catch regressions if the server changes the `verification_uri_complete` format.\\n\\n6. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:83] Token file path printed to stdout could leak path info**\\n\\n   `fmt.Fprintf(outW, \\\"Login complete. Saved token to %s\\\\n\\\", store.FilePath())` prints the full path to the auth file. This is helpful for development but in production could expose the home directory path. This is a very minor concern since it is a local CLI tool, but consider whether this is appropriate for the final UX.\\n\\n7. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/store.go:46-61] `SaveToken` does not validate the token value**\\n\\n   `SaveToken` accepts any string as a token, including empty string. If the server returns `{\\\"access_token\\\": \\\"\\\"}` due to a bug, the code in `waitForApproval` (login.go:125-126) catches this and returns an error. But if `SaveToken` is called directly from other code paths in the future with an empty token, it would silently save an empty value. A guard in `SaveToken` would be defensive:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   if strings.TrimSpace(token) == \\\"\\\" {\\n       return errors.New(\\\"cannot save empty token\\\")\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n8. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go:67,104-106] `client_id` is hardcoded as `\\\"entire-cli\\\"` in two places**\\n\\n   The string `\\\"entire-cli\\\"` appears in both `StartDeviceAuth` (line 67) and `PollDeviceAuth` (line 105). This should be a constant to avoid drift:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   const clientID = \\\"entire-cli\\\"\\n   ```\\n\\n   If the client ID ever needs to change, having it in one place prevents one method from using the old value.\\n\\n9. **[cmd/entire/cli/api/base_url.go:34-46] `ResolveURLFromBase` does not validate the base URL scheme**\\n\\n   A user could set `ENTIRE_API_BASE_URL=ftp://evil.com` and the CLI would attempt to POST form-encoded data to an FTP URL. While this is user-controlled and would fail at the HTTP transport level, validating the scheme early would produce a clearer error message:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   if base.Scheme != \\\"http\\\" && base.Scheme != \\\"https\\\" {\\n       return \\\"\\\", fmt.Errorf(\\\"base URL must use http or https scheme, got %q\\\", base.Scheme)\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n10. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:108-109] The `\\\"\\\"` and `\\\"authorization_pending\\\"` combined case obscures intent**\\n\\n    This was raised in review-01 item 3. The combined `case \\\"\\\", \\\"authorization_pending\\\":` makes it unclear that `\\\"\\\"` is the success path. Even though the code works correctly, a reader must trace through the second `if result.Error == \\\"\\\"` check to understand the flow. Splitting them would make the success path explicit in the switch. Reiterating because this is a readability concern that affects long-term maintainability.\\n\\n11. **[cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/login_test.go:240-243] `waitFn` captures both stdout and stderr into a single string**\\n\\n    The `wait()` function concatenates remaining stdout with stderr: `string(stdoutBytes) + stderr.String()`. This means assertions on the output cannot distinguish between stdout and stderr. For the current tests this is fine, but it makes it harder to add assertions like \\\"error message appears on stderr, not stdout.\\\" Consider returning them separately or at least adding a separator.\\n\\n12. **[cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go:76-77] `User-Agent` header is hardcoded as `\\\"entire-cli\\\"` without version**\\n\\n    Including the CLI version in the User-Agent header (e.g., `entire-cli/0.5.0`) would help server-side debugging and analytics. The `versioninfo` package already provides this. However, `auth` package importing `versioninfo` may create an import cycle -- if so, pass the version string into `NewClient`.\\n\\n13. **[cmd/entire/cli/login.go:48] User code displayed but no copy-to-clipboard helper**\\n\\n    RFC 8628 flows often require the user to manually enter the `user_code` at the verification URI (when `verification_uri_complete` is not available). The code prints it but does not offer clipboard copy. This is a UX suggestion for a future iteration.\\n\\n14. **[scripts/local-device-auth-smoke.sh:11-15] Cleanup function does not remove the temp log file**\\n\\n    The `cleanup` trap kills the background process but does not `rm -f \\\"${LOG_FILE}\\\"`. Temp files accumulate across runs. Add cleanup:\\n\\n    ```bash\\n    cleanup() {\\n      if [[ -n \\\"${LOGIN_PID:-}\\\" ]] && kill -0 \\\"${LOGIN_PID}\\\" 2>/dev/null; then\\n        kill \\\"${LOGIN_PID}\\\" 2>/dev/null || true\\n      fi\\n      rm -f \\\"${LOG_FILE}\\\"\\n    }\\n    ```\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- **Token storage implementation is well-engineered.** The atomic write pattern (temp file, fsync, rename) with `0o600`/`0o700` permissions is the standard approach for credential files. Using `jsonutil.MarshalIndentWithNewline` for consistent POSIX line endings is a nice touch that shows attention to detail.\\n\\n- **Integration test architecture is excellent.** Spawning a real CLI subprocess against an `httptest.Server`, piping stdout for prompt parsing, and using mutex-protected server state is a robust approach. The `loginProcess` abstraction is clean and follows the existing `TestEnv` patterns in the codebase.\\n\\n- **Good defensive coding throughout.** The `maxExpiresIn` cap prevents a misbehaving server from keeping the CLI waiting indefinitely. The `maxPollInterval` cap prevents `slow_down` from spiraling to absurd intervals. The `maxResponseBytes` limit on JSON decoding prevents OOM from malicious responses. The scheme check in `openBrowser` prevents non-HTTP URL execution.\\n\\n- **RFC 8628 compliance is solid.** All five error codes from Section 3.5 (`authorization_pending`, `slow_down`, `access_denied`, `expired_token`, and a `default` catch-all) are handled. The `grant_type` URN is correct. The `slow_down` backoff increment matches the 5-second recommendation.\\n\\n- **Clean package structure.** Separating `apiurl`, `auth` (client + store), and the `login` command into distinct packages with clear responsibilities. The `apiurl` package is reusable for future API endpoints. The `Store` struct with path injection via `NewStoreForPath` enables easy testing.\\n\\n- **README updates are well-placed.** The \\\"Local Device Auth Testing\\\" section with the smoke test instructions and the `--print-browser-url` tip for development are helpful for onboarding contributors to this feature.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n- **Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n- **Key concerns:**\\n  1. All 8 critical/important items from review-01 remain unaddressed.\\n  2. The poll loop should handle transient server errors (5xx) gracefully rather than aborting the entire login flow (new item 1). A single blip during a 5-15 minute polling window should not kill the session.\\n  3. Test coverage gaps are significant (new item 2): `slow_down`, `maxPollInterval`, unknown error codes, and empty token edge cases have zero test coverage. These are the most complex branches in the feature.\\n  4. The hardcoded `\\\"entire-cli\\\"` string appears in two places without a constant (new item 8) -- a simple fix that prevents drift.\\n- **Estimated effort:** 2-3 hours to address all outstanding items from both reviews. The code quality is high overall; the issues are targeted fixes rather than architectural problems.\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":346,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":59346,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":346,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":25,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ2moNjAw1u5i4aTj2AHZ\",\"uuid\":\"fc39f77c-18e4-4b36-b26d-b4e7cadd7e62\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a713062a872c2d8d3\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01NTuMV5ZbpfAYdR7H5mQQ8y\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01H6xkMdUbRJbb54L58NNMnv\",\"uuid\":\"00153844-03ac-490d-9337-38f61053204d\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T09:58:29.752Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"6045d8ec-bf58-4e40-89fe-f1126e592103\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\