0Z\"},\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a780d382b3082c7f6\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_011149RC5FJJ5HK2RWN7js25\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_0177wTfe321Uo6r8f35wYLRw\",\"uuid\":\"a778b495-f712-4747-a008-6f75413aa84b\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T12:58:06.071Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"6045d8ec-bf58-4e40-89fe-f1126e592103\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\"slug\":\"synthetic-puzzling-torvalds\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"a778b495-f712-4747-a008-6f75413aa84b\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Agent\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code post-task\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01NEY4XnFNkEjj53VfbFKyjh\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01NEY4XnFNkEjj53VfbFKyjh\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T12:58:28.732Z\",\"uuid\":\"542120d3-92c5-4721-82ab-edce4ebed085\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"6045d8ec-bf58-4e40-89fe-f1126e592103\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\"slug\":\"synthetic-puzzling-torvalds\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"d83d9e0e-af3c-4126-90b9-436a8fc1ab93\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"promptId\":\"949f04fc-7808-4592-80ee-822dc01333f5\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01NEY4XnFNkEjj53VfbFKyjh\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here is my efficiency review of the device auth code.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Efficiency Review: Device Auth Code\\n\\n### Finding 1 -- `decodeJSONWithOptions` double-buffers unnecessarily\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, lines 177-192\\n**Severity:** Low\\n\\n`decodeJSONWithOptions` reads the entire body into a `[]byte` via `io.ReadAll`, then wraps it in a `bytes.NewReader` to feed to `json.NewDecoder`. This allocates the full response body twice in memory (once as `[]byte`, once as the decoder's internal buffer). Since `io.LimitReader` is already applied, `json.NewDecoder` could be used directly on the limited reader:\\n\\n```go\\ndec := json.NewDecoder(io.LimitReader(r, maxResponseBytes))\\n```\\n\\nThis would eliminate the intermediate `[]byte` allocation entirely. The only reason to buffer first would be to provide better error messages that include the raw body text, but that is not done here -- the error just wraps the decode failure. For a 1MB max response this is not a real problem in practice, but it is unnecessary work.\\n\\n### Finding 2 -- `BaseURL()` re-reads env var on every call (but impact is negligible)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/api/base_url.go`, lines 20-26\\n**Severity:** Low (informational)\\n\\n`BaseURL()` calls `os.Getenv` and `strings.TrimSpace` on every invocation. However, I note that `NewClient` in `client.go` (line 55) captures `apiurl.BaseURL()` once at construction time and stores it in the struct field `c.baseURL`. Similarly, `LookupCurrentToken` in `store.go` (line 72) calls it once per invocation. So this is already mitigated by the callers. The per-request hot path uses `c.baseURL`, not `BaseURL()` directly. No action needed.\\n\\n### Finding 3 -- Poll-loop tests sleep for real wall-clock time\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/login_test.go`, lines 59-78 (and others)\\n**Severity:** Medium\\n\\nTests that exercise the poll loop (e.g., `TestWaitForApproval_PendingThenSuccess`, `TestWaitForApproval_SlowDown`, `TestWaitForApproval_TransientErrorRetry`, `TestWaitForApproval_TransientErrorCounterResets`) pass `interval: 0` to `waitForApproval`. When `interval` is 0, `pollInterval` falls back to `fallbackDeviceAuthPollInterval` which is `time.Second` (line 17 of `login.go`).\\n\\nEach pending/error iteration does a real `time.After(pollInterval)` sleep of 1 second. For example:\\n- `TestWaitForApproval_PendingThenSuccess` -- 2 pending iterations = ~2 seconds of wall-clock sleep\\n- `TestWaitForApproval_TransientErrorRetry` -- 2 error iterations = ~2 seconds\\n- `TestWaitForApproval_TransientErrorCounterResets` -- 8 error/pending iterations = ~8 seconds\\n- `TestWaitForApproval_SlowDown` -- 1 slow_down iteration = ~6 seconds (1s base + 5s backoff)\\n- `TestWaitForApproval_TransientErrorExhausted` -- 4 error iterations (5th fails immediately) = ~4 seconds\\n\\n**Total: roughly 22 seconds of unnecessary sleeping across the test suite**, even with `t.Parallel()`. The fix would be to either (a) accept the poll interval as a parameter/option so tests can pass a tiny duration, or (b) use a clock abstraction that tests can control (e.g., a `func() <-chan time.Time` field). This is the most impactful finding for developer iteration speed.\\n\\n### Finding 4 -- `readAPIErrorResponse` applies `maxResponseBytes` limit; `decodeJSON`/`decodeJSONStrict` also apply it -- consistent\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, lines 142-158 and 177-192\\n**Severity:** None (positive observation)\\n\\nThe `maxResponseBytes` limit is applied consistently across all response-reading paths: `readAPIErrorResponse` (line 143) uses `io.LimitReader(resp.Body, maxResponseBytes)`, and `decodeJSONWithOptions` (line 178) does the same. There are no unbounded reads. This is correct.\\n\\n### Finding 5 -- No TOCTOU race conditions detected\\n\\n**File:** All reviewed files\\n**Severity:** None (positive observation)\\n\\nThe check-then-act patterns here are safe:\\n- `waitForApproval` checks `time.Now().After(deadline)` at the top of each loop iteration. There is a theoretical scenario where the deadline passes between the check and the poll call, but this only means one extra poll attempt, which is benign for a user-facing flow.\\n- The keyring store operations (`SaveToken`, `GetToken`, `DeleteToken`) are atomic operations on the OS keyring and do not have check-then-act patterns.\\n- `NewClient` captures `BaseURL()` once at construction, so there is no race between reading the env var and using it.\\n\\n### Finding 6 -- `readAPIErrorResponse` reads full body then unmarshals; could skip on empty body\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, lines 142-159\\n**Severity:** Low (informational)\\n\\n`readAPIErrorResponse` reads the full body, then tries `json.Unmarshal`. If the body is empty, it still allocates and runs `Unmarshal` before falling through to the empty-text check. This is negligible for correctness and performance since it only runs on error paths, but a `len(body) == 0` early return would be marginally cleaner.\\n\\n### Finding 7 -- `PollDeviceAuth` treats all non-200 as soft errors with structured parsing\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, lines 126-132\\n**Severity:** Low (design observation)\\n\\n`PollDeviceAuth` on non-200 responses calls `readAPIErrorResponse` and, if it successfully parses a JSON `{\\\"error\\\": \\\"...\\\"}` body, returns it as a `DeviceAuthPoll` with the `Error` field set (line 131). This means that if the server returns a 400 with `{\\\"error\\\": \\\"slow_down\\\"}`, it is correctly handled by the poll loop. However, if the server returns a non-200 with a body that is not valid JSON or has no `error` field, it falls through to a hard error (line 129). This asymmetry is correct per the OAuth device auth spec (RFC 8628), where error responses should be JSON. No issue here, just noting the design.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n| # | File | Severity | Finding |\\n|---|------|----------|---------|\\n| 1 | `auth/client.go:177-192` | Low | `decodeJSONWithOptions` double-buffers response body unnecessarily |\\n| 2 | `api/base_url.go:20-26` | Low | `BaseURL()` re-reads env var each call, but callers already cache it |\\n| 3 | `login_test.go` (multip