ference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"d83d9e0e-af3c-4126-90b9-436a8fc1ab93\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"6045d8ec-bf58-4e40-89fe-f1126e592103\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\"slug\":\"synthetic-puzzling-torvalds\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"e738d404-7c5c-4cc9-a0c5-2c4976b64371\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Agent\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code post-task\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01R9HGENjdutxFUBDxk4QDEz\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01R9HGENjdutxFUBDxk4QDEz\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T12:58:33.255Z\",\"uuid\":\"8a54a27b-2878-4d80-b742-67615dd839e8\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"6045d8ec-bf58-4e40-89fe-f1126e592103\",\"version\":\"2.1.76\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\"slug\":\"synthetic-puzzling-torvalds\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"048356f2-84aa-41be-a71b-4f1a99445f30\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"promptId\":\"949f04fc-7808-4592-80ee-822dc01333f5\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01R9HGENjdutxFUBDxk4QDEz\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Here is my review of the device auth code across all five files.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 1: Duplicated request-building logic in `StartDeviceAuth` and `PollDeviceAuth`\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, lines 63-98 vs 100-140\\n\\nBoth methods follow the same sequence: resolve URL, build `url.Values` body, create `http.NewRequestWithContext` with POST, set the same three headers (Accept, Content-Type, User-Agent), call `c.httpClient.Do`, close body. The only differences are the endpoint path, the form fields, and the response handling. A private helper like `postForm(ctx, path, values) (*http.Response, error)` would eliminate roughly 15 lines of duplication and ensure all future endpoints consistently set the same headers.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 2: `\\\"\\\"` case grouped with `\\\"authorization_pending\\\"` in switch, then re-checked below\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/login.go`, lines 126-147\\n\\nThe switch statement handles `case \\\"\\\", \\\"authorization_pending\\\":` together with a comment \\\"continue below\\\", then line 142 re-checks `if result.Error == \\\"\\\"` to extract the token. This is structurally confusing -- the `\\\"\\\"` case is the success path but it's grouped with a non-success case and the actual success handling is deferred to after the switch. A clearer structure would be:\\n\\n```go\\nswitch result.Error {\\ncase \\\"\\\":\\n    if result.AccessToken == \\\"\\\" {\\n        return \\\"\\\", errors.New(\\\"device authorization completed without a token\\\")\\n    }\\n    return result.AccessToken, nil\\ncase \\\"authorization_pending\\\":\\n    // no-op, will sleep and retry below\\ncase \\\"slow_down\\\":\\n    ...\\n```\\n\\nThis eliminates the post-switch `if` check entirely and makes the success path explicit.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 3: Stringly-typed OAuth error codes\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/login.go`, lines 127-139\\n\\nThe OAuth error strings `\\\"authorization_pending\\\"`, `\\\"slow_down\\\"`, `\\\"access_denied\\\"`, `\\\"expired_token\\\"` are used as bare string literals. These are RFC 8628 defined values that would benefit from being named constants, either in the `auth` package (since they describe API responses) or in `login.go`. This would prevent typos and make the code self-documenting. The `DeviceAuthPoll.Error` field could also document that it uses these constants.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 4: Duplicated `\\\"entire-cli\\\"` string across packages\\n\\n**Files:**\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, line 18: `clientID = \\\"entire-cli\\\"`\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/store.go`, line 12: `keyringService = \\\"entire-cli\\\"`\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, line 80: `User-Agent` header literal `\\\"entire-cli\\\"`\\n\\nThree separate uses of the string `\\\"entire-cli\\\"` with three different semantic meanings (OAuth client ID, keyring service name, User-Agent). Today they happen to share the same value, but they serve fundamentally different purposes. The User-Agent on line 80 (and line 118) is a raw string literal rather than using the `clientID` constant that already exists in the same file. At minimum, the User-Agent headers should reference the `clientID` constant instead of repeating the literal.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 5: `runLogin` has 6 parameters\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/login.go`, line 50\\n\\n```go\\nfunc runLogin(ctx context.Context, outW, errW io.Writer, client deviceAuthClient, openURL browserOpenFunc, printBrowserURL bool) error\\n```\\n\\nSix parameters is on the edge. The two writers and the bool are presentation concerns, while the client and openURL are dependencies. A lightweight `loginOptions` struct could group the non-context parameters:\\n\\n```go\\ntype loginOptions struct {\\n    outW, errW      io.Writer\\n    client          deviceAuthClient\\n    openURL         browserOpenFunc\\n    printBrowserURL bool\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis is borderline -- six parameters is not egregious for a top-level orchestrator, but it would become a clear improvement if any additional parameters are added in the future.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 6: `NewClient` captures `baseURL` at construction time -- no way to override\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, lines 48-57\\n\\n`NewClient` calls `apiurl.BaseURL()` at construction time and stores the result. This means the base URL is frozen when the client is created, even if `ENTIRE_API_BASE_URL` changes afterward. This is probably fine in practice (env vars rarely change mid-process), but it means there is no constructor that accepts an explicit base URL. If a caller wanted to talk to a different server (e.g., in integration tests), they'd need to set the env var before constructing the client. Consider accepting an optional base URL parameter, or adding a `NewClientWithBaseURL` constructor for testability.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 7: `PollDeviceAuth` conflates HTTP errors with OAuth protocol errors\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, lines 126-132\\n\\nWhen the server returns a non-200 status, `PollDeviceAuth` parses the response body for an error string and returns it as a successful `DeviceAuthPoll` with the `Error` field set. This means the caller cannot distinguish between \\\"server returned HTTP 400 with `authorization_pending`\\\" (expected per the RFC -- some implementations use 400 for pending) and \\\"server returned HTTP 200 with a token\\\". The approach works, but it means genuine server errors (HTTP 500 with an error body) get folded into the same code path as OAuth protocol flow errors. The `waitForApproval` function in `login.go` will treat an HTTP 500 `\\\"server_error\\\"` as a terminal failure (the default case) rather than a transient error eligible for retry, because it arrives as `result.Error` rather than as a Go `error`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 8: `decodeJSONStrict` used for `StartDeviceAuth` but `decodeJSON` used for `PollDeviceAuth`\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go`, lines 93 vs 135\\n\\n`StartDeviceAuth` uses `decodeJSONStrict` (which calls `DisallowUnknownFields()`), but `PollDeviceAuth` uses `decodeJSON` (which allows unknown fields). This inconsistency is likely intentional (the poll response may include extra fields from different server states), but it is not documented. A brief comment on line 135 explaining why lenient decoding is used here would prevent a future contributor from \\\"fixing\\\" it to be strict.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 9: No test coverage for `runLogin`\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/login_test.go`\\n\\nThe test file has thorough coverage of `waitForApproval` but no tests for `runLogin` itself. The `deviceAuthClient` interface and `browserOpenFunc` type were clearly designed for testability, and `runLogin` has pure-function-style injection of all its dependencies. The happy path (start -> open browser -> wait -> save token) and key error paths (start fails, browser fails with fallback message, save fails) would be straightforward to test. This is a gap given that the interface was purpose-built for testing.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Finding 10: `openBrowser` calls `cmd.Start()` then `cmd.Process.Release()` -- no error from the child process\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/login.go`, lines 180-187\\n\\nThe function starts the browser process and immediately releases it (detaches). If the browser command fails to actually open (e.g., `xdg-open` exits with an error because no desktop session exists), the error is silently lost. This is a deliberate fire-and-forget design, which is reasonable for browser-opening, but it means the \\\"Warning: failed to open browser automatically\\\" message on line 68 will only trigger for errors during `Start()` (e.g., command not found), not for the browser failing to open the URL. Worth a comment documenting this intentional limitation.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe most impactful findings are:\\n\\n1. **Finding 2** (switch/if confusion) -- straightforward readability win\\n2. **Finding 1** (duplicated request building) -- reduces code and ensures consistency\\n3. **Finding 4** (User-Agent literal vs existing constant) -- trivial fix, prevents drift\\n4. **Finding 7** (H