e.go` | 12 | `keyringService = \\\"entire-cli\\\"` |\\n| `versioncheck/versioncheck.go` | 175 | `req.Header.Set(\\\"User-Agent\\\", \\\"entire-cli\\\")` |\\n| `telemetry/detached.go` | 49 | `machineid.ProtectedID(\\\"entire-cli\\\")` |\\n\\nNote that these serve different semantic purposes:\\n- **OAuth `client_id`** -- protocol-level identifier registered with the server\\n- **HTTP `User-Agent`** header -- identifies the CLI in HTTP traffic\\n- **Keyring service name** -- OS keyring namespace\\n- **Machine ID salt** -- hashing salt for telemetry\\n\\nWhile they all happen to use `\\\"entire-cli\\\"`, they are semantically distinct. Changing the User-Agent should not change the keyring service name, for example. However, a shared constant for at least the User-Agent header (used in `auth/client.go` and `versioncheck/versioncheck.go`) would reduce drift risk.\\n\\n**Verdict: Low-risk duplication with a nuance. The `User-Agent` string should be a shared constant. The `clientID`, `keyringService`, and machine ID salt are semantically different and should remain separate even though they have the same value.**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 5. `decodeJSON` / `decodeJSONStrict` Patterns\\n\\n**Finding: Three independent JSON decode patterns exist across the codebase.**\\n\\n1. **`auth/client.go` lines 169-192** -- New `decodeJSON` / `decodeJSONStrict` / `decodeJSONWithOptions` helpers that read from `io.Reader`, apply `LimitReader`, and optionally enforce `DisallowUnknownFields()`. Used for HTTP response bodies.\\n\\n2. **`settings/settings.go` lines 145-147, 163-166** -- Uses `json.NewDecoder(bytes.NewReader(data))` with `DisallowUnknownFields()`. Operates on `[]byte` (file contents), not `io.Reader`.\\n\\n3. **`versioncheck/versioncheck.go` line 189** -- Uses `io.ReadAll(io.LimitReader(resp.Body, 1<<20))` followed by a separate `parseGitHubRelease(body)` function -- the JSON parsing is downstream, not inline.\\n\\n4. **`trail/store.go` lines 171, 184, 199, 254, 428** -- Uses `json.NewDecoder(reader).Decode(...)` directly on git object readers. No size limiting needed since these are from the local git object store.\\n\\n**Verdict: The `auth/client.go` helpers are well-written but narrowly scoped. The settings package operates on `[]byte`, and the trail/checkpoint packages operate on trusted local git objects -- neither would benefit from sharing the same `decodeJSON` helper. No actionable reuse opportunity at this time.**\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary of Actionable Findings\\n\\n1. **Shared User-Agent constant (low effort, prevents drift)**: The `\\\"entire-cli\\\"` User-Agent string is hardcoded in both `auth/client.go` (lines 80, 118) and `versioncheck/versioncheck.go` (line 175). A single exported constant in the `apiurl` package (e.g., `const UserAgent = \\\"entire-cli\\\"`) would prevent these from drifting apart.\\n\\n2. **Shared response size limit constant (low effort)**: `auth/client.go` defines `maxResponseBytes = 1 << 20` while `versioncheck/versioncheck.go` uses the inline literal `1<<20`. If a shared constant were added alongside the User-Agent constant, both packages could reference it.\\n\\n3. **No other reuse gaps**: The `apiurl` package, browser-open function, keyring store, `decodeJSON` helpers, and OAuth client are all either new (no pre-existing code to consolidate) or appropriately scoped to their packages. The `clientID`, `keyringService`, and machine ID salt intentionally use the same string value but serve different semantic purposes and should remain independent constants.\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: a780d382b3082c7f6 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 35535\\ntool_uses: 17\\nduration_ms: 79333</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"dce0e72e-c823-4438-82b6-6d0983a41ff1\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-14T12:58:50.014Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"You are the Code Reuse reviewer. Search the existing codebase for utilities and patterns that the new device auth